'''Laurel S. Braitman''' (born February 11, 1978) is an American science historian, writer,<ref name=simonandschuster>{{cite web|title= Animal Madness by Laurel Braitman |url= http://pages.simonandschuster.com/animalmadness-facebook/ |website= [[Simon & Schuster]]}}</ref> and a TED Fellow.<ref>{{cite web|title= Laurel Braitman -- TED Fellow |url= http://www.ted.com/profiles/521178/fellow |publisher= [[TED (conference)|TED]] |date= 2014-06-30 |accessdate= 2014-06-30}}</ref>

She is Writer-in-Residence at the [[Stanford School of Medicine]]<ref name=stanford>{{cite web|title= Stanford Medicine |url= https://med.stanford.edu/medicineandthemuse/ProgramPeople.html |website= Stanford Medicine}}</ref> and a Contributing Writer for Pop Up Magazine.<ref>{{cite web|title= Pop-Up Magazine |url= http://popupmagazine.com/issues/fall-tour-2015-la/ |website= Pop-Up Magazine}}</ref>
She is also an affiliate artist at the [[Headlands Center for the Arts]]. Her work has appeared in The Guardian,<ref>{{cite web|title= Animal Behavior |url= https://www.theguardian.com/science/2014/oct/04/animal-behaviour-laurel-braitman |website= The Guardian |location= [[London]] |date= 2014-10-04 |accessdate= 2015-09-16}}</ref>  The Wall Street Journal, Fast Company,<ref>{{cite web|title= Dog Complex |url= https://www.fastcompany.com/3037493/pet-week/dog-complex-analyzing-freuds-relationship-with-his-pets |website= Fast Company |location= [[New York City]] |date= 2013-10-23 |accessdate= 2015-09-16}}</ref> The New Inquiry,<ref>{{cite interview |last= Browne |first= Andrew Springer |interviewer= Laurel Braitman |title= Marijuanimals |url= http://thenewinquiry.com/essays/marijuanimals/ |website= [[The New Inquiry]] |date= 2013-04-19 |accessdate= 2014-06-30}}</ref> Salon,<ref>{{cite web|last= Harris |first= Malcolm |title= Suicidal dogs and bipolar wolves |url= http://www.salon.com/2012/09/26/suicidal_dogs_and_bipolar_wolves/ |website= [[Salon (website)|Salon]] |date= 2012-09-26 |accessdate= 2014-06-30}}</ref> and a variety of other publications.

Laurel frequently collaborates with visual artists<ref>{{cite web|title= Art & Science Transdisciplinary Lectures: Laurel Braitman, Historian. The Zookeeper’s Couch |url= http://www.newschool.edu/eventDetail.aspx?id=55602 |publisher= [[The New School]] |date= 2010-09-14 |accessdate= 2014-06-30}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title= Galápagos Chorus |url= http://www.annhamiltonstudio.com/performances/galapagoschorus.html |website= [[Ann Hamilton (artist)|Ann Hamilton Studio]] |accessdate= 2014-06-30}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title= Human/Nature Credits |url= http://www.artistsrespond.org/credits/ |website= Human/Nature: Artists Respond to a Changing Planet |accessdate= 2014-06-30}}</ref> and musicians<ref>{{cite web|last= |first= |title= Video: Grass Widow Plays Music for Gorillas at the Zoo |url= http://www.thefader.com/2011/08/01/video-grass-widow-plays-music-for-gorillas-at-the-zoo/ |website= [[The Fader]] |date= 2011-08-01 |accessdate= }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last= Thompson |first= Barry |title= How Grass Widow came to play a concert for a small group of great apes |url= http://portland.thephoenix.com/life/124766-how-grass-widow-came-to-play-a-concert-for-a-small/ |website= [[The Phoenix (newspaper)|The Phoenix]] |date= 2011-08-04 |accessdate= 2014-06-30}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title= Understanding the animal mind... through music |url= http://www.bbc.com/future/story/20120731-musical-minded-animals |publisher= [[BBC]] |date= 2012-07-31 |accessdate= 2014-06-30}}</ref> like [[Black Prairie]] to create concerts for all-animal audiences, such as wolves.<ref>{{cite web|title=Making Music For Animals |url= http://www.studio360.org/story/making-music-for-animals/}}</ref>

== Biography ==

Braitman was born and raised on a citrus farm near [[Ventura, California|Ventura]]<ref name=LitLovers>{{cite web|title= Animal Madness - Laurel Braitman - Author Biography |url= http://www.litlovers.com/reading-guides/14-non-fiction/9872-animal-madness-braitman?start=1 |website= LitLovers |location= [[Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania]] |date= June 2014 |accessdate= 2014-07-01}}</ref> in southern [[California]].<ref name=NPRintern>{{cite web|title= Intern Bios |url= https://www.npr.org/about/jobs/01intern/bios.html |publisher= [[NPR]] |accessdate= 2014-07-01 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=KFA Rights Guide |url=http://www.graal.com.pl/sites/default/files/katalogi/KFA%20Rights%20Guide%20October.pdf |publisher=The Karpfinger Agency |location=[[New York City]] |date=October 2013 |accessdate=2014-06-30 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140714190018/http://www.graal.com.pl/sites/default/files/katalogi/KFA%20Rights%20Guide%20October.pdf |archivedate=2014-07-14 |deadurl=yes |df= }}</ref> She majored in Biology and Writing at [[Cornell University]], where she was a member of the [[Quill and Dagger]] society and graduated [[summa cum laude]].  She worked as an intern in the ''Weekend Edition Saturday'' program at [[NPR]].<ref name=NPRintern/>  She received a John S. Hennessey scholarship to pursue graduate studies at the [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]], where in 2013 she received her PhD in the history and anthropology of science. Braitman lives in [[San Francisco]], California.<ref name=LitLovers/>

== Works ==

She is the author of ''Animal Madness: How Anxious Dogs, Compulsive Parrots, and Elephants in Recovery Help Us Understand Ourselves'', which was published in October 2015. In the book, Braitman shows through a wealth of research that nonhuman animals are startlingly similar to us in how they are affected by mental illness, and in what methods best help them recover.<ref name=amazon>{{cite web|title=www.amazon.com |url= https://www.amazon.com/Animal-Madness-Inside-Their-Minds/dp/1451627017/ref=sr_1_1?ie=UTF8&qid=1454382552&sr=8-1&keywords=animal+madness+inside+their+minds}}</ref><ref name=simonandschuster/>

